ne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","Corbie,80800,Somme,Picardie,FRANCE,":"Corbie, Somme, Picardie, France","Péronne, Somme, Picardie, France":"Péronne, Somme, Picardie, France","Péronne, Somme (80), FRA":"Péronne, Somme, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Péronne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Pasquale, Angelo, Deno, Dino, Francesco, Orazio, Vito.","Italian: from an augmentative of the personal name   Pero  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pero","meanings":["Italian: from the personal name <i>Pero</i>, a variant of <i>Piero</i> ‘Peter’ (see   Pieri  ).","Galician: from the personal name <i>Pero</i>, Galician equivalent of   Peter  .","Portuguese: habitational name from any of the places called Pero."]}]},{"name":"Charles","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Germanic word, <i>karl</i>, meaning ‘free man’, akin to Old English <i>ceorl</i> ‘man’. The name, Latin form <i>Carolus</i>, owed its popularity in medieval Europe to the Frankish leader  Charlemagne  (  ?742–814 ), who in  800  established himself as Holy Roman Emperor. His name (Latin <i>Carolus Magnus</i>) means ‘Charles the Great’. <i>Carolus</i>—or <i>Karl</i>, the German form—was a common name among Frankish leaders, including Charlemagne's grandfather  Charles Martel  (  688–741 ). <i>Charles</i> is the French form. The name occurs occasionally in medieval Britain as <i>Karolus</i> or <i>Carolus</i>; it had a certain vogue in West Yorkshire from the 1400s, particularly among gentry families. The form <i>Charles</i> was chosen by  Mary Queen  of Scots (  1542–87 ), who had been brought up in France, for her son, <i>Charles James</i> (  1566–1625 ), who became  King James VI  of Scotland and, from  1603 ,  James I  of England. His son and grandson both reigned as  King Charles , and the name thus became established in the 17th century both in the Stuart royal house and among English and Scottish supporters of the Stuart monarchy. In the 18th century it was to some extent favoured, along with   James  , by Jacobites, supporters of the exiled Stuarts, opposed to the Hanoverian monarchy, especially in the Highlands of Scotland. In the 19th century the popularity of the name was further enhanced by romanticization of the story of ‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’, leader of the  1745  rebellion."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Charles de Péronne was born in 1202, in Péronne, Somme, Picardie, France, his father, Robert de Péronne III, was 34 and his mother, Eleonore de Roucy, was 19. He married Alice de CORBIE in 1232, in Corbie, Somme, Picardie, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1266, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1202–1266":"1202–1266","1201–1259":"1201–1259","1216–1267":"1216–1267","1233–1256":"1233–1256","1242–1304":"1242–1304","1254–1312":"1254–1312","1168–1239":"1168–1239","1183–1246":"1183–1246","1242":"1242","1198":"1198","1183":"1183","1239":"1239","1304":"1304","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1202":"1202","1246":"1246","1312":"1312","1256":"1256","1168":"1168","1267":"1267","1201":"1201","1233":"1233","1266":"1266","1232":"1232","1254":"1254","Ro